United States: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It is even comical that Barack Obama, a renowned wise man, has repeated his predecessor's strategy on the Afghan issue, which he himself considered to be simple.
When he finally let loose his long-awaited doctrine, it turned out he had copied it to carbon paper from Bush's Iraq script from three years ago.
Not content with using the phrase "as in Iraq" several times in the text itself, he did not hesitate, moreover, to use the title of Bush's January 2007 speech as the title of his own speech: "A New Road Forward"
At the same time, he personally criticized Bush's idea of sending new reinforcements into a civil war-torn Iraq as being "irresponsible and a decision with catastrophic consequences".
The following months, however, showed that Bush's strategy, which was based on the recommendations of the campaign commanders, was the only one possible and likely to succeed to such an extent that the newspapers at present do not mention Iraq at all.
This did not improve Bush's reputation, but objectively speaking, it left his successor with a far more favorable end than could have been hoped for.
Barack Obama hopes that in Afghanistan, the miracle will happen again
It was again the campaign commanders who asked him for an increase in the military contingent, including the commander of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who even harshly criticized the reluctance of the White House despite the subordination habits.
He asked for 40,000 men so he could make the situation more favorable.
The president hesitated for three months, but for want of a better option, he at least conned the general of 10,000 soldiers.
He managed to get the promise of 5,000 more from Europe, even though he had originally counted on 10,000.
What seems to be the most problematic aspect of the whole Obama strategy is his intention to withdraw the troops from Afghanistan within 18 months and to complete the whole process within three years.
Many doubt that a halving of the increase will produce the same results as the progress in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized and its leaders honor agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is the exact opposite - no one can be counted on and no treaty is respected.
Under these conditions, it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, accustomed to changing leaders day by day as they see fit.
Political institutions, though officially established, will remain as a powder in the eye for the proliferation of patriarchal ethnic relations.
Balancing the interests of the various ethnic groups is particularly complex given the lack of clarity about the relationships, which are further complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even the establishment of a "state of prompt action", which is the basic aim of the operation, does not seem very real.
The time horizon of Obama's strategy is puzzling because of his voluntarism.
Over the last eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only gotten worse and is now on the brink of chaos.
Only a purely romantic, unrealistic heart can be convinced that the little soldiers sent into the turmoil of war for their "immediate return home" will bring about a real miracle.
From a political point of view, setting a date for the withdrawal of troops is purely irresponsible since the Taliban will view it as an indirect admission of American defeat.
The latest NATO summit showed that the European willingness to participate in military operations in Afghanistan is moving in the negative direction.
European politicians do not know or want to explain to their voters how security in Germany or Italy is linked to a war in the Hindu Kush mountains.
Another factor that could radically alter the situation is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the tightened sanctions do not have an effect on the Iranians, the Americans will find themselves faced with the very difficult question of solving the problem by military force.
The answer will have to be found, for example, when, according to Obama, America will successfully withdraw its troops from Afghanistan.
Any such solution will, however, lead to a dramatic reversal of the situation in Afghanistan.
The only rusty thing for Obama is the fact that there are three years left until the presidential election and therefore there is still plenty of time for him to plan a new strategy, in case it turns out to be a total fiasco.
