Czech discovery: a substance that works on "hard" HIV viruses too
A team of Czech and German scientists is testing new combinations that can slow the spread of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also acts on viruses that have already developed immunity to the drugs.
This reality is in some cases overridden by the fact that the combination does not act as intensely on common variants of the virus as some already available drugs.
There is no cure for AIDS at present.
Nevertheless, the lives of patients can be greatly extended by a combination of drugs that prevent the HIV virus from multiplying in the body.
However, their consumption has a number of side effects.
In addition, suppressing this multiplication results in the development of so-called drug-resistant viruses that are no longer effective against drugs.
The work of experts from three institutions, the Czech Academy of Sciences, VŠCHT Prague and Heidelberg University, paves the way for a way to address virus resistance.
They showed that substances called metallocarborans act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
Metalocarborans are an assembly of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
This combination blocks the development of the virus in a way that is different from all the drugs used so far and that is why they could overcome the problem of resistance.
The researchers' work leads them to discover new "improved" substances, based on their knowledge of the molecular mechanics of their binding to virus proteins.
Metallocarborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-walled cages are formed by the boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms and connected by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus.
HIV protease is a protein in the HIV virus that is essential to the life cycle of the virus.
Without the division of the HIV virus by the HIV protease there would be no formation of mature infectious virus particles.
Stopping the HIV protease also stops the virus from spreading into the patient's body, the researchers said in a press release from the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry at the Czech Academy of Sciences.
In their work published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, the scientists describe a series of combinations where two pairs of cages (see table) are connected by a short organic chain, which is then systematically modified.
A little weaker, but more reliable.
The effectiveness of this series of substances on HIV proteases has been tested in test tubes and on resistant variants obtained in HIV-infected patients.
On the common version of the enzyme, the effect of the metallocarborans is not as strong as on clinical drugs, however it does not weaken on resistant versions against which common drugs are often ineffective.
Therefore, metallocarborans, with their unique mechanism of action and other properties such as their biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical modifications, are interesting combinations to further investigate in the development of effective HIV drugs, says Pavlína Řezáčová, director of the Structural Biology Laboratory at the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics at the Academy of Sciences.
