But it was seen as a major step forward in the time-consuming negotiations, with more than 100 world leaders arriving in Copenhagen next week.
The report, prepared by a UN task force, does not say how much the rich countries would give to the poor to help with the current and long-term climate change.
And it offers a wide range of options for key issues, including how developed and emerging economies could reduce their carbon emissions and what would be the upper limit of global temperature rise that officials would be willing to tolerate.
It gives the process a great deal of flexibility, said John Coequyt, Washington representative of the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote six pages of the document, studied a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN's Executive Secretary-General on Climate Change, Yvo de Boer, described as "the full picture".
It provides guidelines for a possible agreement in which industrialized nations would collectively reduce their emissions by 2020 by 25 to 45 percent from 1990 levels, while major developing countries, over the same period, would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent.
Together, the countries would reduce emissions by between 50 and 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union also revived negotiations on Friday, pledging to provide $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change -- to withstand floods and drought or to prevent deforestation.
However, on Friday, the same verbal altercations occurred, which have dominated the negotiations since last week.
Todd Stern, US Representative at the Climate Negotiations rejected any discussion of forcing industrialized countries to reduce greenhouse gases, compared to voluntary efforts by major emerging economies, if these were not financed by developed countries.
This change is a signal that the Obama administration is getting tougher on China than the Bush administration was two years ago.
The US will not sign an agreement without efforts and actions from major developing countries, said Stern, who also regretted that the text did not stress enough to ensure that the cuts could be verified by outside observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after China's Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei said the top US negotiator was either "lacking common sense" or "extremely irresponsible" for saying earlier this week that the US would not help China financially to fight global warming.
With the future economic trajectories of the major world powers at stake, flaws have emerged both within the Third World and between the industrialized world and the emerging economies.
The current battle is more about saving individual economies than saving the planet, with China and the US fighting over their respective obligations while poorer nations insist that the two dozen most influential countries ignore the scientific imperatives to act more boldly.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it was not surprising that the major powers were fighting over who should bear the costs of reducing greenhouse gases, even as vulnerable countries became more aggressive in their attempt to hold the big emitters accountable for their actions.
It is really a game in which a new economic hegemony is being developed, said Ulate, who is also Climate Advisor for Mexico and Central America for Conservation International.
Some of these countries more vulnerable to the impact of climate change have indicated that they will continue to press for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most of the main participants say that negotiations will lead at least to a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which has 43 members, drafted a 24-page draft treaty early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, head of the European Commission's climate unit, said the action of the small island states has "put political pressure on the whole political process", partly because they are now united and are calling on emerging economies such as China and India to act.
The debate became an urgent affair, as delegates focused on the fact that they had to solve most of the outstanding problems before the heads of government could reach an agreement.
High-level officials such as India's environment minister Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese vice minister got off their planes and rushed to the Bella Center building to attend closed-door meetings and information conferences, so they could make complaints that would be considered in the following week.
The real picture of the rally -- where 13,000 people walk in and out of the Congress Palace every day -- of activists playing guitar and putting on nightly shows mocking countries that they say are betraying each other and proposals are written and distributed on paper rather than by email -- is a real challenge.
The intensity is only increasing: almost all the important ministers are here and 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen no later than Wednesday.
We are entering the court of the great", said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, vice president for global policy at Conservation International.
The heavyweights are coming.
In Britain, the first train running at 225 km/h will redefine Monday syndrome
At 5:13 a.m. on Monday morning, a whistle will blow through the night to signal the departure of a train that will revolutionize transportation in Britain.
The country's first high-speed commuter train will reach 225 km/h, as it runs from Ashford, Kent, to London St Pancras, covering 93 km in 38 minutes.
Lord Adonis, the Secretary of State for Transport, will be joined by Dame Kelly Holmes on board the first Javelin commuter train outside London.
He hopes the new service will allow Britain to be part of a fast and reliable international rail network and will link the major conurbations of the Midlands, North and Scotland to London.
Small, lost holes will become thriving suburbs, business travel times will be much shorter, and the switch from air and car to train will reduce national carbon emissions while reducing traffic jams on the roads.
In theory, the three main political parties are in favour of this project.
But the ten billion pounds needed to build a new railway network, the inevitable scheduling battle and fears of environmental hazards risk holding back Britain's high-speed railways.
According to The Times, High Speed Two (HS2), a company set up in January to produce a feasibility report for the government, will hand over its paper to Lord Adonis on December 30.
This will allow it to obtain a detailed map of the route of the next planned stage of the high-speed network.
The new line between London and the West Midlands will be drawn within 15 feet of the urban area and sites where environmental impact may be controversial.
In the countryside, the plan will be drawn up to 25 meters from the final route.
It is also planned that HS2 will present three options for a larger high-speed network, going north.
Lord Adonis will answer in the spring.
The preferred options are highlighted in a Y-shaped configuration for which a high-speed line will go to the West Midlands.
The line will split in two at or near Birmingham, with one branch going west of the Pennines to Manchester and Scotland and another going north-east to Sheffield, Leeds and Newcastle upon Tyne.
A single line will run through Scotland.
"It seems to be the best performance option", said one railway professional.
When it's complete, the travel time between London and Edinburgh will be reduced to 2 hours 40 minutes.
The first branch, which will not open until 2025, will allow all passengers to travel between London and Birmingham in 49 minutes, compared to an hour's journey currently.
The proposals will allow the train to travel at 400km/h, making the UK network the fastest in the world.
The initial route is designed to accommodate trains 400 m long and carrying 1100 people.
Up to 18 trains per hour can run on a London - Birmingham line.
A terminal with a capacity of 20000 passengers per hour would be needed.
Given the space constraints, it is planned to enlarge an existing station to accommodate the high-speed network.
The rail industry experts say that only St Pancras International or Euston offer this possibility.
Lord Adonis will announce whether or not he thinks the project should go ahead, but longer public consultations and planning procedures mean that a final decision will not be made until a general election.
Even if he starts the machine, the network will have to be built piece by piece.
Trains will first be required to run off high-speed lines on existing tracks north of Birmingham, keeping travel times between London and Scotland over three hours.
This seems to be the best solution for the transition from airplanes to trains, and is a reference point for the rail revolution.
Taxpayers pay back the £75,000 loan for the Tory orange shop
Alan Duncan, the leading Tory MP, has made the taxpayer pay thousands of pounds a year to cover the cost of an orange grove he built in his home in his riding.
The party leader who was demoted by David Cameron for complaining that MPs were "underpaid" has increased his loan of £75,000 to build an oak extension to his second home in Rutland.
He was authorized to charge the taxpayer extra interest, amounting to hundreds of pounds a month.
The Commons authorities received the complaints at the time and were not questioned by Sir Thomas Legg, who is overseeing the members' expenditure.
Mr Duncan, one of the wealthiest Members of Parliament, owns a two-storey house in a village in his constituency of Rutland-Melton.
The houses next door were sold for almost a million pounds.
The ground floor includes a kitchen, living room and dining room, but the tax office says Mr. Duncan needed more space.
Last year, he added a veranda to the house, describing it in his plans as an orange grove.
Neighbors describe it as a "veranda for fun".
Mr Duncan was not asked to explain the increase in borrowing during a recent investigation by the Commons Privileges and Standards Committee into his pre-borrowing arrangements.
The committee cleared him last month of any charges of breach of the rules after an investigation into his expenses.
In 2004, Mr Duncan changed the legal security of the £271,406 loan from his London property to his riding house which he bought in 1991, the year before he became an MP.
Documents released this week show that Mr Duncan was claiming about £1,400 a month in borrowing interest until March last year.
In April, his demands increased by over £1,800 a month.
The interest rate on Mr Duncan's RBS loan was unchanged at that time, suggesting that all the increases were intended to finance the GBP 75,000 loan.
The standard variable rate of RBS has fallen from 7.94% in December 2007 to 4% in March this year and has not moved since.
The latest publication from the Commons authorities shows that Mr Duncan was still asking for £1,250 in May.
Mr Duncan lost his position as Shadow Cabinet Secretary in September after an undercover journalist allegedly filmed him saying that MPs had to survive "on budget" after the spending scandal.
"In fact, it's now national, you have to live on a budget and you're treated like a...
He said: "I spent my money on my garden and asked for a small part, based on what was right.
and I could have asked for a hell of a lot more, but I didn't".
The MP, a millionaire from his former job as an oil trader, began to have to explain his expenses in May after it emerged that he had asked for thousands of pounds for his garden, before agreeing with the fees office that this "could be considered excessive".
An activist dug a £ hole in Mr Duncan's lawn to protest after it was revealed he had been asking for £4,000 for three years.
Asked about the loan increase last night, Mr Duncan said: "It was for major improvements, approved by both the expense bureau and Legg".
He added: "There is no problem of dodging or making or using rules or anything.
It was very clear, in the rules, authorized, etc.
It couldn't be clearer or simpler".
Fellows, come and see the Brighton Advent Calendar.
Brighton beach cabins have found a new way to promote the winter months, an interactive Advent calendar.
Beyond, an alternative church group that encourages spiritual exploration through creativity, invited 24 homeowners to decorate their cabin for each day of December, using Christmas carols as a theme.
The event began on December 1, when visitors were allowed to visit the last booth, from 5:30 to 6:30 p.m. daily, with free pastries and hot wine served.
The Christmas songs chosen so far include "I Saw Three Ships, O Come, O Come, Emmanuel and The First Christmas", for which the booth features work by Janette Tozer, a local artist.
Martin Poole, 50, a TV marketing assistant in Hove, is an unpaid priest in the Diocese of Chichester and Director of Beyond.
He said: "We want religion to be closer to people in a post-Christian society.
"Why, as a church, do we wait for people to walk into an old, strange building?
"The idea for the Advent calendar from the beach cabin came just after a conversation with a few friends over dinner.
Brighton is such a creative and vibrant place and we try to experience and represent that through spirituality".
Strong mobilisation in Copenhagen and around the world for climate
Tens of thousands of people demonstrated on Saturday to demand an ambitious and binding agreement on fighting global warming, worldwide and in Copenhagen, where police made several hundred arrests.
At least 30,000 people, according to police, and 100,000 according to organizers, marched in the cold in the Danish capital on the sidelines of the UN Climate Conference, which is expected to reach an agreement by Friday that could come into force on January 1, 2013.
Connie Hedegaard, the Danish chair of the climate conference, said the growing global climate mobilisation, illustrated by these demonstrations, had helped make "the political price" of failure in Copenhagen very high.
The incidents in the Danish capital took place shortly after the march had started, when a group of 300 protesters, all dressed in black, smashed windows with cobblestones and hammers, an AFP reporter reported.
Riot police quickly responded without mercy.
In total, police said they had arrested 600 to 700 people, mostly members of what they said were the "black blocs", the ultra-violent groups that were at the NATO summit in Strasbourg, eastern France, in April.
The Climate Justice Action (CJA) coalition, one of the organizers of the rally, denounced the conditions under which hundreds of activists were arrested "without distinction", noting that about 100 of them "were still held in the street on Saturday night" handcuffed and kept in a sitting position despite the extreme cold.
The party, rather a good kid, took the lead at the Bella Center, the site of the negotiations.
The protesters stopped about 500 meters from the building, without trying to enter.
A stage was set up for the planned speakers, before a candlelight vigil attended by former South African Archbishop of Cape Town, Desmond Tutu.
Most of the protesters had come by bus and train from major European cities, but many Asians, including some Chinese and Koreans, were also present as well as Africans.
Nearly 3,000 people, mostly in raincoats, had formed an early morning rally in Copenhagen at the invitation of Friends of the Earth, who were to form "blue tides" for "climate justice".
Today we are taking to the streets to demand compensation for the ecological debt to the South, said Lidy Nacpil, a Filipino activist with the Jubilee South Coalition in Copenhagen.
We cannot keep saying we have time, said the Beninese singer Angélique Kidjo.
There are rivers that dry up in Africa, streams where you can walk like you've never walked before.
For the first time in the history of climate diplomacy, which began in 1992 with the adoption of the UN Convention, the alter-globalism movement has come closer to environmental organizations.
The French MEP José Bové, a figure in the alter-globalism movement, said he had come to Copenhagen to "link climate justice and social justice": "Today, there is no separation between the fight against global warming and the fight for another world".
The Asia-Pacific region, home to many islands particularly vulnerable to warming, had sparked protests.
Some 50,000 people, according to organizers, took to the streets in Australia.
In Manila, a few hundred people, mostly students, marched in red, holding banners touting solar energy.
In Hong Kong and Jakarta, as well as in Canada, rallies of a few hundred demonstrators were also held to demand vigorous action against climate change.
In France, demonstrations organised by the 350 network drew a few hundred people, notably in Paris, Marseille (south), Lille (north), Bordeaux (west) and Lyon (east).
In Geneva, a few dozen people gathered.
Abkhazia elects president, Georgia says it is a "farce"
Abkhazia elected its president on Saturday, a little over a year after Moscow recognized the pro-Russian separatist region of Georgia, while Tbilisi denounced it as a "farce".
Some 131,000 people were scheduled to participate in the first election after the August 2008 Russian-Georgian war for control of South Ossetia, another breakaway Georgian territory recognized by Russia.
The polls closed at 5:00pm GMT.
The turnout was 58 percent hours before the closing, according to Abkhazian election commission officials.
The first provisional results were to be announced in the night from Saturday to Sunday.
The five candidates, including outgoing president Sergey Bagapch, categorically reject the idea of reunification with Georgia, which condemned the holding of the election.
This election is a sham.
For his part, Georgian President Mikheil Saakashvili "regrets that Abkhazia has fallen under the total occupation of Russia", said his spokeswoman, Manana Manjgaladze.
In addition to Russia, only Nicaragua and Venezuela have recognized the independence of this territory of 216,000 inhabitants, while the rest of the world considers it part of Georgia illegally occupied by Russian troops.
After seceding from Georgia in the 1992-93 conflict that killed thousands, Abkhazia is seeking to show through this election that it is ready to join the international community.
This process is a step in our new life, our new era as an independent state, said Svetlana Kvartchia, a 54-year-old historian who said she voted for Mr. Bagapch.
She was among the voters who went to the polling station in a school in the capital, Sukhumi, in a beautiful white building with some palm trees in front of the entrance.
The issue of Russian domination is at the heart of the presidential election in this region with its lavish scenery on the Black Sea.
Large signs showing Mr. Bagapch with Russian President and Prime Minister Dmitry Medvedev and Vladimir Putin are scattered throughout this small territory of 216,000 inhabitants.
In Gali, in the west of the country, the district head Beslan Archba warmly welcomed the Russian officials who had come to monitor the election.
We, the Abkhaz people, are grateful, he said at a small ceremony, alluding to Moscow's support, particularly the decision to recognize Abkhazia's independence.
I hope that your country will soon be recognized by the United Nations", replied Alexei Ostrovsky, a member of the Russian parliament, raising a glass of vodka.
The opposition, represented in the election by former vice-president Raoul Khadjimba and two businessmen, Zaous Ardzinba and Beslan Boutba, criticized agreements with Moscow last year, such as the one ceding control of Abkhazian railways to Russia for 10 years.
The fifth candidate, Vitali Bganba, says he supports neither the current government nor the opposition.
A 50% majority plus one vote is required to win the election.
If no candidate reaches this threshold, a second round must be held within two weeks.
