Geo-history comes out stronger from the reform of the general high school, according to Chatel
The Minister of National Education Luc Chatel said in an interview to be published in the JDD on Sunday that history and geography were coming out "strengthened" by the reform of the general high school, despite the abolition of their compulsory teaching in science terminals.
Now all first-year students will have four hours a week and the same curriculum for a shared common culture, says Mr Chatel.
The minister said that "hypocrisy must be removed" because, in his view, "School S is no longer a science school" but "in general, it concentrates the best students".
The ES and L courses cannot remain sub-fields of the S, he continues, stressing further: "I have also not heard many historians and intellectuals express indignation at the absence of history and geography as a final subject in technological high schools".
On Saturday, an Ifop poll published in L'Humanité revealed that almost seven in ten (69%) French people disapproved of the government's plan to remove compulsory history and geography in the S-level. Many intellectuals and teachers also criticized the removal, as did the left and some right-wing elected officials.
The Minister added, however, that there was "no question" of removing the philosophy from the S-terminal programme.
Luc Chatel also defended the reform of teacher training, while 16 organizations (students and unions) called for a day of mobilization on Tuesday to protest the project, which they say sacrifices the pedagogical training of future teachers.
In the master's degree (M2), they will pass an admissibility test at the beginning of the year, which will cover their discipline, and then at the end of the year an admission test, which will cover their ability to teach, the minister explained.
They will also undertake practical training during the M2 year and then be a first year in front of the pupils as trainee teachers.
If you add up all the courses offered before the competition, you already get more presence in front of the students, or more than 300 hours, he continued.
Finally, the minister said he would propose "the individual right to training, which does not exist in the National Education".
He also reaffirms the plan to abolish the school card "by 2012".
At Normal Sup, experts have 15 minutes to convince about the climate
Fifteen minutes to talk about the issues at the Copenhagen summit: this was the challenge posed on Saturday morning by Jean Jouzel, Vice-President of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC), invited by the Ecole Normale Supérieure de la rue d'Ulm.
Jean Jouzel, also a Nobel Peace Prize winner, opened the first of the "Ernest" conferences, a day of a series of expert talks, each 15 minutes long, filmed and open to the public, an AFP reporter said.
We wanted to do something that would catch people's eye and make them want to know more", said 22-year-old Edouard Hannezo, one of the organizers of the event, which is named after the fish that students gave to the school's swimming pool.
He said that about 20 speakers were chosen from experts in their fields and selected for their charismatic side.
On global warming, "you can talk in hours, but you can also talk about key targets in minutes", said Jean Jouzel, who spoke without notes but with graphs in front of about 50 people.
This is part of our role as scientists, he stressed, hoping that the listeners will remember that 'the Copenhagen conference is based on a very serious scientific dossier'.
Videos from these lectures will be posted on the school's website from 15 December.
The next "Ernest" day is scheduled for February, followed by others at a bimonthly rate.
Late payments: anger from prison officials, action planned
The prison supervisors' unions called for a "general mobilisation" on Friday to demand payment by the end of the year for bonuses and overtime, which was postponed to January for budgetary reasons.
FO-penitentiary (2nd supervisors' union) asked the staff who will not be on duty to demonstrate on Tuesday morning in front of the prison institutions and "block" them, to "denounce the theft of their debts".
The CGT-penitentiary (the third trade union) calls on them to "meet in general assemblies in the various prisons for a strong mobilisation", judging "shameful and unacceptable" the non-payment in December of "overtime, night, Sunday and holiday bonuses" worked in October.
And the leading supervisors' union, the Federal Independent Prison Union (Ufap/Unsa), "calls for a general mobilization . . . to raise discontent and anger".
The Directorate of Prison Administration and the Ministry of Justice explain that overtime has increased significantly in 2009 and not all of it has been budgeted, but assure that the remainder will be paid in January.
The Chancellery said late in the day that Michèle Alliot-Marie had sent a letter to the supervisors' unions assuring them that the payment would be made next month.
I am aware of the efforts made by the staff to operate and modernize our prison system, the Minister of Justice wrote in this letter.
I have asked the prison administration to put in place without delay a package of measures to ensure that this situation, which is the result of a miscalculation of the number of overtime hours, does not happen again in the future, adds Ms Alliot-Marie.
The December salary will therefore be meagre, except for the executives who enjoy the famous bonuses for their jobs and objectives, lamented the UFAP/Unsa, for whom "budgetary constraints are a good thing".
This is a pure scandal, the interregional association FO of Marseille has said, announcing its decision to boycott "all meetings and conventions" until further notice.
The staff will not come to work on their Sundays and public holidays if the October ones are not regularised in December, the same for overtime, also threatens FO Rhône-Alpes-Auvergne.
At a time when we are increasing our tasks and missions without increasing our staff, it is more than regrettable to dare to attack the staff's money, says the CGT-penitentiary of Bordeaux.
According to the trade unions, the situation is not the same in all regions, with some less badly off than others.
But the number is not there, said Ufap's secretary-general, Jean-François Forget.
For Christmas, Obama says he's offering "cooler tricks" than he gets
President Barack Obama, who is preparing to spend his first Christmas with his family in the White House, told Oprah Winfrey that he had a simple rule when it came to gifts: "I give better things than I get".
In a special Sunday night show on ABC, the president and his wife Michelle offer a glimpse into how they plan to celebrate the holidays in their new, prestigious home.
Even Bo, the family's little four-legged companion, will be in on the action.
Michelle Obama said Santa also loves Bo, adding that the dog would "of course" get a gift, according to pre-release clips of the show.
And Michelle Obama has registered false against her husband's claims about the quality of the gifts he receives: "Of course not, I got you cool gifts last year", she teased the president.
Absolutely, was he forced to concede before he humorously responded by pointing to the first lady's pearl necklace: "Who gave you this?"
During this hour-long, casual show with the famous host who was a huge supporter of Barack Obama during the presidential campaign, the president and his wife also recalled their favorite gifts as children.
Barack Obama spoke of a ten-speed bicycle, but also a basketball that his Kenyan father, whom he rarely saw, gave him for Christmas.
I remember one time I met my father who came to visit us for Christmas and gave me a basketball, the president said.
It wasn't until much later in my life that I realized that he was the one who gave me that ball.
The first lady remembered her side of her dollhouse.
I really didn't know how to organize a house, so I had all the furniture lined up against the wall, rather than arranging it around the fireplace, but I loved this little dollhouse", Michelle Obama said.
