Johnny Hallyday underwent re-operation in Los Angeles due to extensive "injuries" after an operation in France, but the situation is "under control" according to his entourage, while RTL claims the singer has been placed in an artificial coma to avoid pain and complications.
The 66-year-old rock star underwent a second operation on Wednesday night at Cedars-Sinai Hospital in Los Angeles after American doctors found "operation-related damage" to his herniated disc in Paris on November 26, his Paris press office said, adding that the damage "needed repair surgery".
The singer's press office, however, reassured that the situation was "under control", while announcing that a new medical report would be issued within 48 hours.
According to RTL, the singer's partner on his latest tour, Johnny Hallyday was put into an artificial coma to avoid "pain and complications".
Only after 48 hours, when the patient opens an eye, will we know a little more about his condition, RTL reports.
Asked by AFP, the press service neither confirmed nor commented on the information.
RTL also claims that "according to some sources" no drainage was laid after the first operation in Paris.
The rocker had surgery at the Monceau Park International Clinic for this herniated disc.
The procedure, which had been scheduled for several days, was performed by neurosurgeon Stéphane Delajoux, a well-known doctor in the art world.
He was not available on Thursday evening to comment on RTL's report.
Following the surgery he performed on Johnny Hallyday, the singer was hospitalized Monday at Cedars-Sinai Hospital in Los Angeles for an infection following the surgery.
