The birthplace of the dinosaurs
Tawa hallae was similar to other carnivorous dinosaurs: this biped was about 6 feet (2.0 m) long and 5 feet (1.5 m) high, had powerful hind limbs, an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short arms terminated by sickle-like claws, and a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would have had nothing out of the ordinary.
But as Sertling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and his colleagues report in Thursday's Science magazine, the Tawa hallae is one of the first dinosaurs to exhibit these morphological features.
This animal lived 215 million years ago in New Mexico, which was then part of the landmass of the supercontinent Pangea and was located near the equator.
Sertling Nesbitt says the Tawa discovery sheds new light on the evolution of the first dinosaurs.
It tells us about the relationships, distribution, and characteristics of the relatives.
It was in 2006 that Sertling Nesbitt and other paleontologists undertook excavations at the Gohst Ranch site in northern New Mexico.
Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History and a member of the excavation team says that they sometimes found a dozen bones in a day, which is absolutely unique for a sedimentary layer from the Triassic.
Scientists quickly realized that some of these bones belonged to a new species.
The excavations have brought up the remains of five specimens.
A discovery that confirms theories about the beginning of dinosaur evolution.
The researchers named it Tawa after the Hopi Indian word for the sun god.
Sterling Nesbitt said it was a remarkable discovery. Dinosaur fossils from the Triassic are extremely rare and contain only a few incomplete bone fragments.
Not all paleontologists share this enthusiasm.
For example, Martin Sander of the University of Bonn does not consider this discovery to be particularly spectacular, but he does say that it confirms certain theories about the early evolution of dinosaurs.
According to current knowledge, dinosaurs appeared on Earth about 230 million years ago.
Most of the oldest fossils, however, are fragmented and incomplete, making it very difficult to classify the very first dinosaurs.
The experts are wondering, for example, when the saurians split into three major evolutionary groups: the theropods (carnivores), which include the tyrannosaur and the later velociraptor, from which the birds descended; the sauropods, long-necked quadrupeds, and their relatives; and the ornithischian herbivores, which include species such as the triceratops and the stegosaur.
According to the studies of S. Nesbitt and his colleagues, the Tawa is one of the earliest theropods.
This species has an interesting mix of primitive and developed features, says S. Nesbitt.
Researchers have found evidence suggesting that the Tawa hallae had small air sacs in its skull bones, just as birds descended from theropods do.
These small air pockets make it easier for birds to breathe than mammals.
It seems that in the Tawa hallae, the vertebrae were also partially filled with air.
According to Randall Irmis, the Tawa is one of the oldest theropods with tiny air sacs in its bones.
Since the related lineage of the giant sauropods also had air sacs and a light bone, it may be thought that their common ancestor already possessed this beneficial innovation.
Three successive waves of migration to North America.
Since the earliest known dinosaurs lived in South America, researchers have concluded that the dinosaurs originated there.
So the three major evolutionary lines split and spread from South America to the rest of the world, which is all the land that formed the supercontinent Pangea.
This seems to be confirmed by the fact that the team of paleontologists also discovered the remains of two other theropods that are not particularly related to it.
The three species cannot descend from a common ancestor who migrated, say the researchers.
Alan Turner of the Natural History Museum in New York and co-author of the journal Science Studies says there were at least three waves of migration to North America.
There are of course some contradictions.
Martin Sander, a paleontologist in Bonn, says that there is an even older species, the silsaurus, that lived in what is now Poland and that it belongs to a group related to the dinosaurs.
He said this could give the wrong impression because there are a large number of dinosaur fossils in South America that have been preserved, while there are almost none on other continents.
However, how dinosaurs managed to become the dominant tetrapods of the Second Age from a relatively rare collateral line of the reptile branch remains a mystery to this day.
In the Triassic, dinosaurs shared habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of today's crocodiles and many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Triassic, dinosaurs spread across the planet, fostering the development of many new species while others, related to them, disappeared between the Triassic and Jurassic.
Such success, however, is not permanent.
To explain this transformation, Martin Sander sees two hypotheses.
There may have been a mass extinction in which dinosaurs survived randomly while other reptiles would have gone extinct.
Or maybe dinosaurs were better adapted and so they could eliminate competition on the field.
In any case, such success is not permanent.
150 million years later, a meteorite crash helped to bring about the flourishing of a group of animals that had also developed during the Triassic and had since been largely forgotten: mammals.
