The dream worlds
Some people are awake seeing images and hearing voices that no one else sees or hears.
It is not only in the mentally ill or under the influence of drugs that the boundaries between imagination and reality blur.
As long as these things happen during sleep, everything's fine.
When we lie in our dark rooms, we can indulge in the wildest dreams and fantasies unhindered.
However, the person who, when awake, experiences a dream state, hears and sees things that others do not perceive, soon has the reputation in our Western world of being crazy or drugged, or at least being original.
Such images and voices are not only seen in people with mental illness or under the influence of drugs.
It's our imagination that's at fault -- it's the same neuronal activity that allows us to design houses, paint paintings, or write novels, but sometimes causes the boundaries between dream, madness, and reality to blur.
A state of conscious waking, taking the form of a dream, can take many forms, from visions at best to madness at worst.
But even though the trigger and the effect are distinct, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, the second states of shamans, psychosis and hallucinations are all attributed to very similar processes.
Hallucinations or delusions occur when the balance of neurotransmitters in the brain - primarily dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin and acetylcholine - is broken and the interaction between different parts of the brain is disturbed.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts are very common during schizophrenic psychosis.
The force of gravity no longer has power over the person.
Since ancient times, philosophers and doctors have always looked into the relationship between madness and dreaming.
For Aristotle, hallucinations were a form of daydreaming; Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, noted in 1861 that "madness is very similar to dreaming", and for Sigmund Freud, dreaming was even "a psychosis with all its irregularities, imaginations, delusions and sensory illusions".
