About one percent of the population suffers from schizophrenia at least once in their lifetime, and in psychiatric clinics it is the second most common disorder after depression.
In a schizophrenia crisis, the affected person can no longer distinguish between the inner world and the outer world, and they find themselves in a state of hyperexcitation, which can lead to hallucinations, megalomania, relationship madness or persecution.
It is very common to hear voices  commanding voices, commenting voices or conversing voices.
Optical hallucinations are also not uncommon.
The person concerned can no longer distinguish between the important and the insignificant, the brain can no longer filter out disturbing signals, the conscious is drowned in sensations.
Like dreaming, psychosis opens the floodgates to a flood of ideas and fantasies from the deeper layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is centered on the subject, according to Professor Thomas Fuchs, head of the psychiatry department at the Heidelberg CHU (Allgemeine Psychiatrie im Universitätsklinikum).
The schizophrenic is at the very center of the situation, with a meaning centered on him.
At the same time he finds himself in a passive role, he is like in a dream, overcome by events and cannot act on them actively.
