The Promise of FonPeek
Peek is extremely limited, it is a device that only allows you to look at your e-mail, without offering the possibility even of seeing certain types of attachments or browsing the Internet.
It enjoyed its five minutes of fame in the United States when Time magazine named it one of the products of the year.
It is actually harder to see on the street, but the idea seems interesting, especially for young people.
Unlike smartphones, Peek offers a very low price and monthly subscription, less than half of what, for example, the iPhone data subscription costs.
Following its success, the company launched two new devices: one designed exclusively for Twitter, the other with a free lifetime data service, at six times the price of the Peek.
FonPeek, presented yesterday at the Web event, is the European version of the invention and its third incarnation.
It's as limited as its American cousin, but it comes with a surprise.
The monthly subscription price, around EUR 12, includes roaming throughout Europe.
Those who travel with a Smartphone already know what it's like to give up data when crossing a border or desperately search for a cafeteria on Wi-Fi (or a Fon connection) to check your mail.
The idea of fixed-price roaming is incredibly attractive and should have worked for a long time.
Some operators have special arrangements and travel options, but for me, I would need a PhD in physics to understand them and good glasses to read the fine print.
The European Commission's repeated calls for affordable roaming charges across Europe have had little noticeable effect.
Outside their home country, people are hesitant to use data, and rightly so.
The fact that a small device like the FonPeek (it is always curious that it is called Fon even though it does not have Wi-Fi) offers these types of rates means that operators are starting to think differently and are looking at different proposals to make their data network more profitable.
Kindle is another good example, it includes downloading books and other Internet searches.
No subscription and no hassle.
It is a connected device and you pay when you buy it and not every month.
And that's what I hope to see one day for FonPeek: a lifetime access purchase option like Peek already offers in the US.
Not that I want to buy it.
I'm checking my mail on my phone, thank you.
I simply wish it because I believe it is a fairer formula for the consumer.
It would be interesting to see a computer with this same system.
