75% of working mothers have had work problems because of their maternity
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for younger generation women who want to become mothers.
This is the finding of the study  Fertility and career of women in Spain , carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer.
The survey of 9 737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no doubt: 75% of working mothers have had their working careers limited by maternity.
The study shows that there are many differences in the start of married life and the number of children, whether the woman works or not and the type of job she has.
Women who are not working outside the home, who work parttime or have unstable jobs, marry earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
In contrast, women with stable jobs, mainly in the public sector, delay marriage and first pregnancy and have fewer children.
Women aged 35-49 with a fixed job have their first child on average 3.7 years after they have settled down as a couple.  This figure rises to 4.1 for those working in the public sector.  These data show that women with a fixed job have taken longer in their lives to get it, which has led them to delay marriage and the arrival of children.
Moreover, the type of job exercised has a major influence on maternity, but less on the date of beginning cohabitation, explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
Education is another factor that widen the gap between the age of marriage and the age of first child.
The survey found that the higher the level of education, the later they marry and have their first child.
The difference also persists among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, those with primary and higher education respectively became mothers for the first time at an average age of 25.1 and 32.1 years.
 Another distinction also appears between women, according to their level of education.
While those with primary education marry and have their first child before finding a stable job, those with secondary or higher education reverse this programme and give priority to obtaining a stable job as a prerequisite for marriage and the arrival of a child, says Delgado.
