He does not do this according to the predictable and apprehended genres (biographical summary, life and work), but by looking for something similar to the nucleus of the character created.
The journey is exciting and Vincent is not without its scares and illuminations.
This book is a delightful treat, but it is also a moving invitation to read and reread.
I'll leave you with a few snapshots.
On Albert Camus:  In its pages, I discovered that the Mediterranean was not a sea, but a spiritual, almost physical, impulse, the very one I felt without naming it: pleasure against fate, morality without guilt and innocence without any god. 
On Samuel Beckett:  Nihilist, Christian allegorical, he wrote what was in his blood, not in his head, between powerlessness and ignorance, with a dazzling poetic humor, meaningless, like the blade of the knife that almost killed him. 
On Graham Greene:  Our man was inspired by this woman of passion that lasted thirteen years, in whose flesh he combined the emotion of adultery with the pleasure of remorse, a spiritual privilege that was to reach heaven by the path of perdition. 
On James Joyce:  Ulysses was published in Paris in 1922 by Sylvia Beach.  It is one of the eight thousand-meter peaks of world literature, which must be climbed by the north face, on which the best climbers still and always let go. 
About William Faulkner: He was a strange man.
Of himself he sometimes said he was the heir of a county landowner and other times he was the son of a black woman and a crocodile.
Both of these dreams were great.
On Louis-Ferdinand Céline:  This writer collected the insane scream pushed from a bridge by this character of Munch to carry its echo to the depths of the night of the 20th century, in its literary form, and he did so in flight from himself and invoking posterity with a violent speech to maggots. 
About Dorothy Parker:  One day she got down on her knees and prayed:  Dear God, I beg you to make me stop writing like a woman. 
On Joseph Conrad:  On his grave were engraved the verses of Spenser:  Sleep after toil,/ after the storm the port,/ rest after war,/ after life, tired death delights. 
About Virginia Wolf:  In her luggage she carried her depression too.
Her husband would very normally accept her telling him that Edward VII was peeping among the azaleas or that the birds were singing in Greek.
Never was a man so patient and so in love with a neurosis whose literary talent exceeded madness.
On Pío Baroja:  What did Martín-Santos do but try to hide Joyce at Baroja's?
What was Benet trying to do but have Faulkner shoot Baroja?
What did it do but seek the glory of this man to serve as his pedestal?
