Sales of light commercial vehicles are increasing
After almost two years, the light commercial vehicle market is beginning to see some light at the end of the tunnel.
The 9 425 vehicles registered in November in Spain represent an increase of 12.6% compared to 2008 and, more importantly, they represent the first increase after 22 consecutive months of decline, according to figures from the employers' union of the manufacturers Anfac and Ganvam, the dealer union.
However, there is some good news, as the benchmark for comparison in November 2008 was particularly poor, with a 60% decrease compared to the previous year.
As a result, despite the reversal last month, the number of registrations accumulated during these 11 months is 40% below the previous year.
Since January, if all vehicles falling within the category of light commercial vehicles (derivatives of passenger cars, pickups, vans, light vans and light chassis trucks) are added together, 95,853 have been sold.
The big clouds that are most affecting demand have not disappeared, because although they are also bought by individuals, most of the purchases are made by small and mediumsized enterprises, which pay for almost 100% of their purchases with external financing.
Thus, in addition to the restrictions implied by the limitation of bank credit, other factors such as the increase in unemployment or the persistence of the bad economic situation must be added.
In view of this situation and the difference in passenger cars, the aid for the purchase of the 2000E was of little use.
In addition to individuals, self-employed people and SMEs who wish to purchase a light commercial vehicle of less than 3.5 tonnes with a CO2 emissions level of not more than 160 grams per kilometre can also benefit, but the number of operations speaks for itself.
Yesterday, at Ganvam, we were again reminded of the need for the administration to pay special attention to these vehicles and also to industrial vehicles (trucks and buses).
The dealers' association forecasts a similar year to the one ending in 2010, for which it calculates a fall in sales (for passenger cars and 4x4s) of 19%.
Emergency braking assistance is now compulsory
As was the case with the ABS anti-lock braking system and as will be the case with ESP stability control, emergency braking assistance systems will be a mandatory feature on European cars.
They are already mandatory on newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while a grace period has been set for the rest of the vehicles until the end of February 2011.
The EU-imposed measure aims to improve pedestrian protection, although its mode of action may also help to avoid many rear-end collisions.
The emergency brake assist acts by increasing the pressure on the brakes in the event of an emergency detected by the system by the driver's kick.
But the latter does not always maintain the pressure until the end.
According to a study by the car component manufacturer Bosch, one third of the drivers involved in an accident had failed to apply the brake before the collision, and half of them had not used the brake to its full strength.
Up to 1 100 accidents
The assistance intervention, on the other hand, requires the maximum of the braking system, reducing the distance the car needs to stop.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with these types of components, up to 1 100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided each year.
This reduction would be even greater with the popularisation of so-called intelligent emergency braking systems: it is estimated that one in four accidents with injuries would be prevented.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that, by means of a radar or camera, detects obstacles and warns the driver, and acts slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, he helps by increasing the pressure on the pedal if necessary.
If it does not react, and although the collision is inevitable, the device will apply maximum force to the brakes to minimise damage.
