After rosy days since last spring, when asset inflation was the dominant note in the markets, uncertainty is again emerging, which is not surprising as it is their natural state, in an environment where agents make decisions about a future of uncertain nature.
The remedy used by central banks to stabilise markets has been to monetize debt by buying assets directly and indirectly by providing ample liquidity at near-zero rates, so that financial institutions buy assets to mobilise.
Central banks have already confirmed that direct asset purchases have been virtually completed and, without questioning their non-conformist liquidity policy, are starting to put some sand in the chips, as the ECB has done, with their one-year tender next week.
As a result, investors are questioning the ability of the global economy to sustain economic recovery without heterodox measures and we are seeing a reversal in the reduction in risk premia.
Stock market volatility and corporate bond spreads are rising again, although they remain far from the paranormal levels they reached at the beginning of the year.
The States have been forced to socialize private risk and the public debt is again affected.
There is a return to quality and the US, Japan and Germany have been the safe havens of choice for investors, increasing the differences between the euro area countries and Germany.
Spain was barely affected by this episode of instability, but then Standard & Poor's threatened to downgrade the rating of the Kingdom of Spain again.
On the other hand, a little uncertainty is not bad for silencing the moral hazard advocates, who were once again trying to stir up a sense of conscience among the world economic policy makers who had curbed the destructive effects of the credit limitation on job destruction, when what should be done is to declare a new Thanksgiving.
However, the situation in Dubai is similar to a tribal struggle between the emirates to regain their place in the emirate and we have already seen the case of Greece.
A government that hides a public deficit, elections, and a new government that uncovers the pot of roses.
Prodi did it in Italy after Berlusconi and Socrates in Portugal after Durão Barroso.
It would be completely irrational for the ECOFIN to bail out Hungary from non-compliance with its external payments at the beginning of the year and allow a euro area country to default on its commitments.
What is logical, however, is that ECOFIN has encouraged the Greek government to be transparent and has made its citizens jointly responsible for the need for extraordinary measures to maintain the stability of its public finances.
If, as we hope, we are faced with a period of normalisation of transitional risk premia after some excesses in high positions, this would be foreseeable.
In the case of Spain, as long as our public debt spreads grow in line with European corporate bonds, we have nothing to worry about.
If European disparities were to narrow and our own to continue to widen, then this would be an idiosyncratic Spanish risk.
The Standard & Poor's case is an anecdote: when our forecasting indicators force most research services to anticipate their stimulus models and to revise upward their forecasts for 2011, with the OECD and the European Commission also back to the task with a Japanese model for the Spanish economy, it does not bode well for their warning.
Once again, this seems to be a great opportunity to buy Spanish assets, even if for now  prudence is a mother of certainty.
