The President of Iberdrola, Ignacio Sánchez Galán, was the first to speak yesterday before the Congress of Deputies' subcommittee, where the energy strategy of Spain for the next two decades is being discussed.
After his speech, which was followed by that of the President of Gas Natural-Fenosa, Rafael Villaseca, Mr Galán outlined for the press what he had said before the subcommittee at eight o'clock.
According to the Iberdrola president, Spain needs to invest €50 billion by 2020 and €60 billion more between then and 2030 if the nuclear power stations currently in operation remain open.
If this were not the case, the investment needed would not be 60 000 million but 95 000 million.
