Acciona is fighting for its first concession motorway in Australia, a market it already operates in as an energy and water company.
The project is a tunnel estimated at A$1.7 billion (about EUR1.047 billion).
The French company Bouygues and the German company Hochtief are its rivals.
A 5 km tunnel in the Australian city of Brisbane on the east coast is an option to enable Acciona to establish itself in the country as a public works and motorway concessionaire.
The city council hopes to have it ready by the end of 2014.
After choosing the public/private partnership (PPP) to carry out the project, as part of a business plan under the auspices of Ernst & Young, the local authority already has a list of finalists who will be responsible for the construction and operation of the toll.
Pending the submission of their bids in May, the planned investment is A$1.7 billion (about EUR 1.047 million) and the final phase is being contested by three consortia, with a significant presence of European manufacturers.
The group called Transcity is led by Acciona, the only Spanish company listed, and its partners are BMD and Ghella.
The first is one of the largest Australian builders, while the second, based in Italy, is one of the largest European specialists in underground work.
Against Acciona's backdrop, the Northern Direct consortium was formed, with the participation of the British company Laing O'Rourke, the Australian infrastructure manager Transfield and the French construction group Bouygues.
The third and final consortium to pass the test is LBRJV, whose capital is shared between the Australian Leighton (a subsidiary of the German builder Hochtief, which in turn owns the stake of ACS), another local company, Baulderstone (owned by the German Bilfinger Berger group) and the Welsh public works company Razel.
The Australian infrastructure market promises major construction and privatisation, but entry is very difficult, except by acquiring a local construction company.
This strategy was followed by the companies Hochtief and Bilfinger, already mentioned, in addition to their Asian references, and remains an unverified step for the Spanish giants in the sector.
ACS has just gained a foothold in this market with its 30% stake in Hochtief, which owns Leighton.
