New tools for car expertise
In these days of bad weather and accidents, the garage is not the only one that benefits.
Every day, thousands of cars that have been involved in an accident are brought back to a garage, where an expert must assess the damage and the cost of repair.
Each claim is different, and calculating the cost of parts and labour time can be a long and complex job.
Calculating the cost of a repair between EUR 20 000 and EUR 30 000, including parts and labour, can take two to three hours.
However, with the help of the latest computer tools, this would be a matter of minutes.
This is why almost 100% of experts use this type of system.
The service providers and solutions for claims assessment and maintenance are dedicated to gathering the information provided by manufacturers, then processing it and offering it to their customers as a useful tool.
In Spain, Audatex, part of the North American Solera group, is the leading company; 80% of estimates are made with its products.
The other competitors in the field of tools for assessing and producing information on the sector are GTMotive and Eurotax.
Working with manufacturers' data is far from simple.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, commercial director of Audatex, the company in Spain has 63 manufacturers and importers, and each of them provides them with information in a different format.
In addition, the volume of data to be processed is constantly increasing, so that more versions, variants and engines have been launched in the last five years than in the previous fifteen years.
When a new car comes on the market, these companies get to work.
This is a very difficult job, because you have to catalogue every one of the thousand parts of the vehicle and put a price tag on it.
In addition, a graphic  intelligent  of each model is made on which the various parts of a passenger car can be clicked.
If it is a mass-selling model, the work can be done in a week if the process proceeds very quickly.
If it is a low-selling car, it can take three or four months.Currently, Audatex has complete information on 99.2% of cars sold in Spain.
For example, they have information on the most exclusive models, such as Porsches, but not on Ferraris or Lamborghinis.
For vehicles on the road, the figure is over 99%.
To carry out the documentation and database development work, Audatex has eight centres around the world (in Spain, France, Germany, the USA, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan), each of which specialises in certain brands.
The national headquarters is located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than 100 technicians (usually mechanical experts) work simultaneously on three computer screens.
Audatex invests 90 million a year in developing these databases.
Every month, 2.5 million data are recorded, and customers receive updates every other day.
The development of this huge flow of information enables these companies to use it for different purposes and to offer a variety of products.
The most common application is for repair and maintenance, but depending on the country, there are also tools for managing scrap parts or calculating the sale or residual value of a car.
The only company that has a guide that gives information on the value of used cars in Spain is Eurotax.
Audatex doesn't offer it in our country, but they do in the United States.
Audatex's products make it easy to see what kind of support it can provide to industry professionals.
The company offers ten different tools, the flagship product being AudaPlus, the standard claims assessment solution for experts.
These include cars, motorcycles, light and heavy industrial vehicles.
In addition to the cost of parts, it takes into account the manufacturer's estimated repair times or painting scales.
This tool is purchased according to its use, for each estimate.
The highest cost is EUR 5.75 for customers who use it only a few times, up to ten times a month.
Then each insurance company, which performs thousands of tests, negotiates its price with Audatex.
Other products, such as AudaVIN, allow the full identification of a vehicle and the equipment with which it left the assembly line, only by its chassis number.
AudaGlass focuses on vehicle glass, and AudaSubastas is an open server for the professional sector on the Internet that allows you to bid on vehicles declared wrecked.
Its statistics service is very useful for identifying trends, conducting geodemographic analyses or knowing common problems by brand or model.
It is possible to study, for example, how many models of a particular brand have gone to the garage for a breakdown or how many have suffered serious accidents for a given period.
GT Motive is the only Spanish company dedicated to the development of this type of tool.
It markets, amongst others, GT Estimate, which is also aimed at experts and provides digital images, as well as access to official parts, prices and times of the manufacturer.
Gt Motive is a company of the Einsa group, founded in 1971 as a provider of claims, breakdowns and maintenance services and solutions.
The GT devaluation guide is a historical reference product on the market.
The company works with 24 000 users in garages, 3 100 experts and 53 insurance companies.
Its turnover has been growing at a rate of 20% a year over the past three years, and it generated a turnover of EUR 10.8 million in 2008.
At the beginning of last year, it began its internationalisation process, with the opening of an office in Paris.
Audatex was founded in Germany in 1966 and established in Spain in 1979.
According to the company's sources, 62% of its turnover is generated in Europe and the rest of the world, and the remaining 38% in North and South America.
The Solera group (Audatex, Sidexa, Informex ABZ, Hollander and IMS) will have a worldwide turnover of USD 557 million, up by 3.3% on 2008.
In our country, the company will receive EUR 19.1 million, 7.2% more than last year.
In 2005, the Solera Group was listed on the stock exchange at $1 billion, today its shares are valued at a total of $2.4 billion.
Since 2007, it has been listed on the New York Stock Exchange and is a component of the Standard & Poor's benchmark index.
Internet auctions of crashed cars
In October last year, the Solera group acquired Autoonline, an Internet platform for the sale of cars, motorcycles and special vehicles in disaster.
The transaction involved a cost of €59.5 million for 85% of the company's capital, which could be increased to the remaining 15% next year.
The aim of the acquisition was to offer more valueadded services to its customers, with the possibility of gaining access to a huge international market.
This estimation and sales service is intended exclusively for professionals in the sector, such as insurance companies, experts, rental companies, garages, salesmen and professional sellers who must be registered before starting operations.
The platform was set up in 1996 in Germany and manages more than 650 000 transactions throughout Europe, including 500 000 in Germany.
Its main markets are Spain, Greece, Poland and Turkey.
There are currently over 1500 vendors and 4000 registered experts on the site.
It handles 3 000 ads a day and in the Spanish market 100 new ads are published every day.
According to Spanish law, a car with a chassis number removed can no longer be driven, but on the other hand, some parts that are not damaged can be used as spare parts.
Old cars can be re-registered, even if they have been withdrawn, after a complex procedure.
Four-stage garage door
With the Auda-Taller tool, Audatex ensures that the user gets a quote in just four steps: identify the vehicle, find the spare part, create a quote and generate it.
The ease of use is a key element of these systems, especially in convincing older professionals who are more or less reluctant to use new management techniques.
The database includes 1,034 vehicles, including 666 passenger cars, 109 off-road vehicles, 137 motorcycles, 78 vans and 44 trucks.
Of course, to use it, you need a computer and an Internet connection.
Once the model to be repaired has been identified by its chassis number, a real graphic image of the model in question appears and the part needed is selected.
The user can include variables such as labour price, increases or reductions, and then print the quote and give it to the customer.
AudaTaller is not an estimation tool like AudaPlus, but a reference catalogue.
The main difference between the two systems is that the one for garages does not include estimated man-hours.
The cost of using this tool for the garage is 350 euros per year, which can be credited.
The Audatex company is currently working on making these images three dimensional.
This is an innovation that mechanics are very keen on, as it will allow, for example, to select a door and rotate it to see the inside.
